  "topic_name": "Heat",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Heat is a form of energy that flows from a hot body to a cold body. Temperature is the measure of the degree of hotness or coldness of a body. Heat is measured in Joules while temperature is measured in degrees Celsius or Fahrenheit. Heat can be transferred by three modes: conduction (through solids without particle movement), convection (through fluids with particle movement), and radiation (without any medium). Metals are good conductors while wood, plastic, and air are bad conductors (insulators). Understanding heat transfer explains many phenomena like sea breeze, land breeze, and cooking.",
    "rules": [
      "Heat: form of energy that flows from hot to cold body.",
      "Temperature: degree of hotness or coldness.",
      "Heat is measured in Joules; temperature in degrees.",
      "Conduction: heat transfer through solids.",
      "Convection: heat transfer through fluids (liquids and gases).",
      "Radiation: heat transfer without any medium.",
      "Metals are good conductors; wood, plastic are insulators.",
      "Dark surfaces absorb more heat; light surfaces reflect more."
    ]
  },
